Recommended model

Use three concepts:

Build tag        = every image build gets a unique tag
Release version  = human-friendly version you promote
Deployment var   = Helm value points to the promoted immutable tag

Example tags:

acr.azurecr.us/gh-runners/ubuntu-runner:2026.05.15-1432
acr.azurecr.us/gh-runners/ubuntu-runner:1.8.0
acr.azurecr.us/gh-runners/ubuntu-runner:1.8.0-20260515.1432
acr.azurecr.us/gh-runners/ubuntu-runner:sha-a1b2c3d

For your use case, I’d use something like:

1.8.0-20260515.1432

or

1.8.0-build.1432

That gives you both a release version and traceability back to the workflow run.

The workflow I’d implement
1. Runner image repo builds the image

On merge to main, schedule, or manual dispatch:

Build image
Scan image
Test image
Push to ACR with unique tag
Generate SBOM/provenance if required
Create GitHub release notes/changelog

Push tags like:

runner-base:1.8.0-build.1432
runner-base:sha-a1b2c3d

Do not overwrite latest for anything deployed.

You can still publish latest for humans/testing, but the Helm deployment should never consume it.

2. Create a release artifact

The release should document:

Runner image: acr.../runner-base:1.8.0-build.1432
Digest: sha256:...
Base image version
GitHub runner version
Installed tools and versions
OS patches applied
Security fixes / CVEs addressed
Breaking changes
Rollback version

This can be a GitHub Release, a CHANGELOG.md entry, or both.


Yes — automate the Helm deployment repo so it dynamically discovers the newest approved image version, but only deploys when the version changes.

The pattern I’d use:

Runner image repo
  builds image
  pushes versioned tag to ACR
  creates release metadata

Helm / ARC deployment repo
  scheduled workflow runs Sunday night
  checks latest approved image version
  compares it to current values.yaml
  if same version: do nothing
  if newer version: update values.yaml
  create PR or deploy automatically
Best practice: scheduled PR, not direct deploy

I would not have the Sunday workflow immediately deploy to prod unless your team is comfortable with that.

Better:

Sunday 2 AM:
  Check latest runner image
  If newer than deployed:
    Open PR updating runnerImage.tag
  If no new version:
    exit cleanly

Then your normal GitOps / Helm deployment workflow runs when the PR is merged.

This gives you automation without surprise deployments.

Option 1 — use GitHub Releases as the promotion source

This is my preferred approach.

Your runner image repo creates a release like:

v1.8.0-build.1432

The release notes contain:

Image: myacr.azurecr.us/gh-runners/ubuntu-runner:1.8.0-build.1432
Digest: sha256:abc123...

Then the Helm deployment repo has a scheduled workflow that checks the latest release tag.

Example:

name: Check runner image version

on:
  schedule:
    # GitHub cron is UTC.
    # This is 7 AM UTC, roughly 2 AM ET standard time / 3 AM ET daylight time.
    - cron: "0 7 * * 0"
  workflow_dispatch:

permissions:
  contents: write
  pull-requests: write

jobs:
  check-runner-version:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - name: Checkout deployment repo
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Get latest approved runner image release
        id: latest
        env:
          GH_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}
        run: |
          LATEST_TAG=$(gh release view \
            --repo your-org/runner-images \
            --json tagName \
            --jq '.tagName')

          echo "latest_tag=${LATEST_TAG}" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT"

      - name: Read currently deployed version
        id: current
        run: |
          CURRENT_TAG=$(yq '.runnerImage.tag' environments/prod/values.yaml)
          echo "current_tag=${CURRENT_TAG}" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT"

      - name: Stop if already current
        if: steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag == steps.current.outputs.current_tag
        run: |
          echo "Already deployed: ${{ steps.current.outputs.current_tag }}"
          exit 0

      - name: Update Helm values
        if: steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag != steps.current.outputs.current_tag
        run: |
          yq -i '.runnerImage.tag = "${{ steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag }}"' environments/prod/values.yaml

      - name: Create pull request
        if: steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag != steps.current.outputs.current_tag
        uses: peter-evans/create-pull-request@v6
        with:
          branch: update-runner-image-${{ steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag }}
          title: "Update runner image to ${{ steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag }}"
          commit-message: "Update runner image to ${{ steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag }}"
          body: |
            Updates the GitHub runner image version.

            Previous version: `${{ steps.current.outputs.current_tag }}`
            New version: `${{ steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag }}`

            Please review the runner image release notes before merging.

Your values.yaml would have:

runnerImage:
  repository: myacr.azurecr.us/gh-runners/ubuntu-runner
  tag: v1.8.0-build.1432
  pullPolicy: IfNotPresent

Then your Helm template or ARC values use:

template:
  spec:
    containers:
      - name: runner
        image: "{{ .Values.runnerImage.repository }}:{{ .Values.runnerImage.tag }}"
        imagePullPolicy: "{{ .Values.runnerImage.pullPolicy }}"
Option 2 — query ACR directly for the latest approved tag

You can also have the deployment workflow query ACR.

Example:

name: Check ACR runner image version

on:
  schedule:
    - cron: "0 7 * * 0"
  workflow_dispatch:

permissions:
  contents: write
  pull-requests: write
  id-token: write

jobs:
  check-acr:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Azure login with OIDC
        uses: azure/login@v2
        with:
          client-id: ${{ secrets.AZURE_CLIENT_ID }}
          tenant-id: ${{ secrets.AZURE_TENANT_ID }}
          subscription-id: ${{ secrets.AZURE_SUBSCRIPTION_ID }}

      - name: Get latest ACR tag
        id: latest
        run: |
          LATEST_TAG=$(az acr repository show-tags \
            --name myacr \
            --repository gh-runners/ubuntu-runner \
            --orderby time_desc \
            --top 1 \
            --output tsv)

          echo "latest_tag=${LATEST_TAG}" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT"

      - name: Read current Helm version
        id: current
        run: |
          CURRENT_TAG=$(yq '.runnerImage.tag' environments/prod/values.yaml)
          echo "current_tag=${CURRENT_TAG}" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT"

      - name: Stop if no change
        if: steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag == steps.current.outputs.current_tag
        run: |
          echo "No new runner image version found."
          exit 0

      - name: Update Helm values
        if: steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag != steps.current.outputs.current_tag
        run: |
          yq -i '.runnerImage.tag = "${{ steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag }}"' environments/prod/values.yaml

      - name: Create pull request
        if: steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag != steps.current.outputs.current_tag
        uses: peter-evans/create-pull-request@v6
        with:
          branch: update-runner-image-${{ steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag }}
          title: "Update runner image to ${{ steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag }}"
          commit-message: "Update runner image to ${{ steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag }}"
          body: |
            Automated runner image update.

            Current: `${{ steps.current.outputs.current_tag }}`
            New: `${{ steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag }}`

However, I like this less unless you are very strict with tags.

Why?

Because “latest tag in ACR” does not always mean “approved for production.”

I would rather promote a tag to GitHub Release or write it to a known metadata file.

Better ACR tagging pattern

Use build tags and promotion tags.

Example image build creates:

ubuntu-runner:1.8.0-build.1432
ubuntu-runner:sha-a1b2c3d

After tests pass, promote by adding:

ubuntu-runner:prod-candidate

But I would not deploy prod-candidate directly.

Instead, the Sunday job resolves what prod-candidate currently points to, extracts the immutable version tag or digest, and updates Helm to that version.

Deployment should still use:

tag: 1.8.0-build.1432

not:

tag: prod-candidate
Option 3 — fully automatic Sunday deployment

This is the more aggressive version.

Sunday 2 AM:
  Check latest approved release
  If different from current:
    update values.yaml
    commit directly to main
    run helm upgrade

I only recommend this for dev or non-prod.

Example flow:

name: Scheduled runner image deployment

on:
  schedule:
    - cron: "0 7 * * 0"
  workflow_dispatch:

permissions:
  contents: write
  id-token: write

jobs:
  deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Get latest approved version
        id: latest
        env:
          GH_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}
        run: |
          LATEST_TAG=$(gh release view \
            --repo your-org/runner-images \
            --json tagName \
            --jq '.tagName')

          echo "latest_tag=${LATEST_TAG}" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT"

      - name: Read current version
        id: current
        run: |
          CURRENT_TAG=$(yq '.runnerImage.tag' environments/dev/values.yaml)
          echo "current_tag=${CURRENT_TAG}" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT"

      - name: Exit if no update
        if: steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag == steps.current.outputs.current_tag
        run: |
          echo "No deployment needed."
          exit 0

      - name: Update values
        run: |
          yq -i '.runnerImage.tag = "${{ steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag }}"' environments/dev/values.yaml

      - name: Commit version bump
        run: |
          git config user.name "github-actions"
          git config user.email "github-actions@github.com"
          git add environments/dev/values.yaml
          git commit -m "Update runner image to ${{ steps.latest.outputs.latest_tag }}"
          git push

      - name: Azure login
        uses: azure/login@v2
        with:
          client-id: ${{ secrets.AZURE_CLIENT_ID }}
          tenant-id: ${{ secrets.AZURE_TENANT_ID }}
          subscription-id: ${{ secrets.AZURE_SUBSCRIPTION_ID }}

      - name: Deploy Helm
        run: |
          az aks get-credentials \
            --resource-group my-rg \
            --name my-aks \
            --overwrite-existing

          helm upgrade --install github-runner-scale-set \
            oci://ghcr.io/actions/actions-runner-controller-charts/gha-runner-scale-set \
            --namespace arc-runners \
            --values environments/dev/values.yaml

Again, I’d keep this for dev/stage, not prod.

My recommended production setup

For prod, I’d do this:

Sunday outside business hours:
  scheduled workflow checks latest approved runner image release
  compares to deployed Helm value
  if new:
    opens PR
  if same:
    exits

Then:

PR merge:
  normal deployment pipeline runs helm upgrade

That gives you:

No latest tag
No surprise redeploys
No deployment if there is no new version
Audit trail through PRs
Easy rollback by reverting the PR
Important detail: “don’t deploy every Sunday”

The workflow should not blindly run helm upgrade every Sunday.

Add a version comparison gate:

if [ "$LATEST_TAG" = "$CURRENT_TAG" ]; then
  echo "No new image version. Skipping deployment."
  exit 0
fi

That is the key piece.

The scheduled job can run every Sunday, but the deployment only happens when the image version has changed.

Best final architecture
runner-images repo
  build image
  push immutable tag
  scan/test
  create approved release

runner-scale-set repo
  scheduled Sunday workflow
  read latest approved release
  compare to current values.yaml
  open PR if different

merge PR
  helm upgrade deploys new image version

This is the cleanest and safest way to mature the process.
